				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Uni=
t of area equal to a quarter of an acre</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Island_of_St._Vincent,_particulars_of_valuabl=
e_freehold_property_-_called_the_Arnos_Vale_Estate,_containing_454_acres_3_=
roods,_or_thereabouts_-_situate_in_the_Parish_of_St._George,_in_the_Island_=
LOC_2015587806-1.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upl=
oad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Island_of_St._Vincent%2C_par=
ticulars_of_valuable_freehold_property_-_called_the_Arnos_Vale_Estate%2C_co=
ntaining_454_acres_3_roods%2C_or_thereabouts_-_situate_in_the_Parish_of_St.=
_George%2C_in_the_Island_LOC_2015587806-1.jpg/250px-thumbnail.jpg" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"393" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"3312" data-file-height=3D"5209"></a><figcaption>Estate for sale o=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Vincent_(island)" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"St Vincent (island)">St Vincent</a>, with area given as=
 454 acres 3 roods (i.e. <span class=3D"frac">454<span class=3D"sr-only">+<=
/span><span class=3D"num">3</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">4</span></sp=
an> acres).</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>rood</b> (<span class=3D"rt-commentedText nowrap"><span class=3D"IP=
A nopopups noexcerpt" lang=3D"en-fonipa"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title=3D"Help:IPA/English">/<span style=3D"border-=
bottom:1px dotted"><span title=3D"/=CB=88/: primary stress follows">=CB=88<=
/span><span title=3D"'r' in 'rye'">r</span><span title=3D"/u=CB=90/: 'oo' i=
n 'goose'">u=CB=90</span><span title=3D"'d' in 'dye'">d</span></span>/</a><=
/span></span>; abbreviation: <b>ro</b><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template=
 Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation need=
ed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (March =
2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>) is a historic English and int=
ernational inch-pound measure of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
rea" title=3D"Area">area</a>, as well as an archaic English measure of <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Length" title=3D"Length">length</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRood_(unit)&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Etymology"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><i>Rood</i> is an archaic word for "pole", from <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Anglo-Saxon_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Anglo=
-Saxon language">Old English</a> <i>r=C5=8Dd</i> "pole", specifically "<a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross" title=3D"Cross">cross</a>", fro=
m <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proto-Germanic" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Proto-Germanic">Proto-Germanic</a> <i>*rodo</i>, cognate to =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Saxon" title=3D"Old Saxon">Old=
 Saxon</a> <i>r=C5=8Dda</i>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_H=
igh_German" title=3D"Old High German">Old High German</a> <i>ruoda</i> "rod=
";<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Rood_(unit)#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the relation of <i>rood</i> =
to <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)" title=3D"Rod (un=
it)">rod</a></i>, from Old English <i>rodd</i> "pole", is unclear; the latt=
er was perhaps influenced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_N=
orse" title=3D"Old Norse">Old Norse</a> <i>rudda</i> "club".
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normandy" title=3D"Norma=
ndy">Normandy</a>, where the rood was also used (before being replaced by m=
etric units around 1800), it was known as a <i>verg=C3=A9e</i>, from the Fr=
ench word <i>verge</i> (stick, rod), which was borrowed in English (see <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virge" title=3D"Virge">virge</a>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Measurement_of_area">Measur=
ement of area</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DRood_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Me=
asurement of area"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Comparison_land_area_units.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=
=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7f/Comparison_la=
nd_area_units.svg/330px-Comparison_land_area_units.svg.png" decoding=3D"asy=
nc" width=3D"298" height=3D"318" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"546"></a><figcaption>Comparison of 1 rood (uni=
t) with some Imperial and metric units of area</figcaption></figure>
<p>Rood is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_unit" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"English unit">English unit</a> of area equal to o=
ne quarter of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acre" title=3D"Ac=
re">acre</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rood_(unit)#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or 10,890 square f=
eet, exactly 1,011.7141056&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup>. A rectangle that is one <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong" title=3D"Furlong">furlong</a>=
 (i.e., 10 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)" title=3D"=
Chain (unit)">chains</a>, or 40 rods) in length and one <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)" title=3D"Rod (unit)">rod</a> in width is =
one rood in area, as is any space comprising 40 <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Perch_(area)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Perch (area)">pe=
rches</a> (a perch being one square rod). The <i>verg=C3=A9e</i> was also a=
 quarter of a Normandy <i>acre</i>, and was equal to 40 square <i>perches</=
i> (1 Normandy <i>acre</i> =3D 160 square <i>perches</i>).
</p><p>The rood was an important measure in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"Surveying">surveying</a> on account of its ea=
sy conversion to acres. When referring to areas, <b>rod</b> is often found =
in old documents and has exactly the same meaning as rood.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rood_(un=
it)#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Linear_measure">Linear meas=
ure</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRood_(un=
it)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Linear measur=
e"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(length)" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Rod (length)">Rod (length)</a></div>
<p>A rood is also an obsolete British unit of linear measure between <link =
rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r115494=
1027"><span class=3D"frac">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D=
"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> and 24 feet (5.0=
=E2=80=937.3&nbsp;m). It is related to the German <a href=3D"https://de.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Rute_(Einheit)" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"de:Rute (Einheit)"=
><i>Rute</i></a> and the Danish <a href=3D"https://da.wikipedia.org/wiki/Da=
nske_m%C3%A5leenheder#L%C3%A6ngde" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"da:Danske m=C3=
=A5leenheder"><i>rode</i></a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Klein2012_4-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rood_(unit)#cite_note-Kl=
ein2012-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Klein1974_5-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rood_(unit)#cite_note-Klein1974-5=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>  The original <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxford_=
English_Dictionary" title=3D"Oxford English Dictionary">OED</a> of 1914 sai=
d this sense was "now only in local use, and varying from 6 to 8 yards" (or=
 18 to 24&nbsp;ft, "Rood", II.7).
</p>
